                                CMD

        CMD stands for Change Main Device. If you don't have a printer
connected to your Amiga, you can use CMD to direct any printer output to
a file on disk.  The disk can then be taken to another Amiga with a printer
connected ant you can print it out from there. To use CMD you need to enter
Tool Types in the icon's Information window. The program comes with default
Tool Types which may work for your system. The Tool Types are:

        DEVICE=<port> The Amiga port to which the printer is attached. The
choices are parallel or serial. Parallel is the default.

        FILE=<filename> The path and name of the file to which the printer
outputs is sent. The default is Ram:CMD_file.

        SKIP=true This tells CMD to ignore any short initial write, for
example a printer reset. The default is SKIP=false, which does not ignore
initial writes.

        MULTIPLE=true Tell CMD to intercept more than one file. The default
is MULTIPLE=false, where only one file is redirected.

        NOTIFY=true Display progress messages while CMD is working, to let
you know whether the operation was successful, and if CMD is still in
operation. The default is NOTIFY=false - no messages will be displayed.

        Double-click on the CMD icon to run the program, and the next time
you send information to your printer it will be redirected by CMD to the
designated file.



